The additional methyl group on the phenyl ring and the dimethyl groups on the cyclohexane ring would further contribute to an increased melting point but to a smaller degree compared to the effect of the rigid, conjugated system. Considering the compound structure and comparing the functional groups' influence, we can do a quantitative estimation for each functional group compared to benzene (which has a generic increase value for each additional cyclic or unsaturated group of about +20 to +30°C due to increased rigidity and possible intermolecular interactions). Dimethyl groups on cyclohexane: +10°C each, cyclohexane-1,3-dione system: +50°C, azo linkage: +20°C, additional phenyl ring: +50°C, an extra methyl group on the phenyl ring: +5°C. Therefore, the predicted melting point is 5.5 (benzene) + 20 (for two dimethyl groups) + 50 (cyclohexane-1,3-dione system) + 20 (azo linkage) + 50 (additional phenyl ring) + 5 (extra methyl group) = 150.5°C
